rdf:Description.NS0:background: Switzerland's independence and neutrality have long been honored by the major European powers and Switzerland was not involved in either of the two World Wars. The political and economic integration of Europe over the past half century, as well as Switzerland's role in many UN and international organizations, may be rendering obsolete the country's concern for neutrality.
rdf:Description.NS0:location: Central Europe, east of France, north of Italy
rdf:Description.NS0:comparativeArea: slightly less than twice the size of New Jersey
rdf:Description.NS0:climate: temperate, but varies with altitude; cold, cloudy, rainy/snowy winters; cool to warm, cloudy, humid summers with occasional showers
rdf:Description.NS0:terrain: mostly mountains (Alps in south, Jura in northwest) with a central plateau of rolling hills, plains, and large lakes
rdf:Description.NS0:environmentalIssue: air pollution from vehicle emissions and open-air burning
water pollution from increased use of agricultural fertilizers
rdf:Description.NS0:literacyDefinition: age 15 and over can read and write
rdf:Description.NS0:localLongCountryName: Schweizerische Eidgenossenschaft (German), Confederation Suisse (French), Confederazione Svizzera (Italian)
rdf:Description.NS0:legalSystem: civil law system influenced by customary law; judicial review of legislative acts, except with respect to federal decrees of general obligatory character; accepts compulsory ICJ jurisdiction, with reservations
rdf:Description.NS0:flagDescription: red square with a bold, equilateral white cross in the center that does not extend to the edges of the flag
rdf:Description.NS0:economyOverview: Switzerland, a prosperous and stable modern market economy with a per capita GDP 20%20 above that of the big western European economies, experienced solid growth of 3%20 in 2000, but growth is expected to fall back to about 2%20 in 2001. The Swiss in recent years have brought their economic practices largely into conformity with the EU's to enhance their international competitiveness. Although the Swiss are not pursuing full EU membership in the near term, in 1999 Bern and Brussels signed agreements to further liberalize trade ties, and the agreements should come into force in 2001. Switzerland is still considered a safe haven for investors, because it has maintained a degree of bank secrecy and has kept up the franc's long-term external value.
rdf:Description.NS0:telephoneSystemDomestic: extensive cable and microwave radio relay networks
rdf:Description.NS0:telephoneSystemInternational: satellite earth stations - 2 Intelsat (Atlantic Ocean and Indian Ocean)
rdf:Description.NS0:illicitDrugs: because of more stringent government regulations, used significantly less as a money-laundering center
transit country for and consumer of South American cocaine and Southwest Asian heroin
